    thinking: "**Clarifying AI-Native Flutter**\n\nI\'m wrestling with a core conflict: I\'m designed as a cloud-based Android build environment for AI Studio, not a native Flutter developer. The directive seems to assume a Flutter development capability that I don\'t possess inherently, given my platform. I need to figure out how to bridge this gap to provide meaningful help with the UI design, considering my architectural constraints.\n\n\n**Re-evaluating Project Scope**\n\nI\'ve hit a roadblock. I realize I can\'t generate Flutter/Dart code due to my environment\'s limitations, which is Android native Kotlin and Jetpack Compose. My system prompt explicitly outlines this. I need to inform the user that I can continue building the app in Kotlin and Compose, as I already did, but cannot switch to Flutter, as requested. I must explain my constraints and offer an alternative path to proceed. The previous turns were all in Android, so I will explain I am optimized for that.\n\n\n**Confirming Implementation Focus**\n\nI\'ve determined my optimal course. Given my constraints, I\'ll explain my capabilities: I can adapt to the requested UI changes or expand the current Android app, which I\'ve been building in Kotlin and Jetpack Compose. I\'ll present this choice clearly, emphasizing my existing work on the Home, Chat, Bookings, and Profile screens, and then offer to expand the app with new features.\n\n\n**Refining Proposal Options**\n\nI\'m now clarifying the solution. Initially, I considered writing Dart code as text, which, while possible, is not ideal given my limitations. My core system directive is to respect user intent. I must maintain the integrity of my environment as an Android-focused build environment. I must refuse the Flutter request, and instead suggest building the required screens in Kotlin and Jetpack Compose, as that aligns with my instructions. It\'s the best path forward given my constraints.\n\n\n**Defining Implementation Details**\n\nI\'m now fully committed to the Kotlin/Jetpack Compose path, as my environment dictates. I\'ve re-reviewed the plan. The user\'s request for Flutter is acknowledged, but I\'ll emphasize my core system directive and limitations. I will complete the Service Detail Screen and Booking Flow screens in Kotlin/Compose to meet the functional requirements, and I will prepare to show my work in `ServiceDetailScreen.kt`, and the Booking Flow screens.\n\n\n**Confirming Android Implementation**\n\nI\'ve decided on my plan. The user explicitly requested Flutter, but my environment is solely for Android development with Kotlin and Jetpack Compose. I\'ll clearly communicate this constraint and explain that I\'m continuing the development of the remaining screens (Service Detail and Create Booking Flow) within the native Android context, allowing them to run and preview the app as designed. I\'ll provide the Kotlin code for `ServiceDetailScreen.kt`. I will now begin `CreateBookingFlowScreen.kt`.\n\n\n**Constructing Kotlin Service Detail**\n\nI\'m now implementing the ServiceDetailScreen in Kotlin and Jetpack Compose. I\'ve focused on the UI elements. Specifically, I have integrated Compose elements, including the TopAppBar with a back button, a scrolling Column for the content, and a \"Book Now\" button at the bottom. The screen currently loads and displays basic data. The layout uses elements such as Image, Text, and Button, and I\'m currently working on adding the functionality. I\'ve begun integrating the Compose elements.\n\n\n**Integrating UI Enhancements**\n\nI\'m now integrating the price and booking elements within the `ServiceDetailScreen`. I\'ve added a Row with price information and a \"Book Now\" button, styled using Compose\'s MaterialTheme for consistent look and feel. The UI features elevation, padding, and text styling for visual clarity, using a Column for layout. I\'m focusing on responsiveness and visual appeal. I have also added `Column` and `Box` for layout.\n\n\n**Adding Content and Styling**\n\nI\'m now populating the ServiceDetailScreen with detailed content and stylistic improvements. I\'m adding a placeholder image, service title, rating details with an icon, and a divider for visual separation. I\'m using Compose elements like `Image`, `Text`, `Row`, `Icon`, and `Divider`. I\'m focused on the visual clarity and overall design. I\'m also ensuring the content is properly formatted and presented.\n\n\n\n**Populating Detail Content**\n\nI\'m now populating the ServiceDetailScreen with detailed content. I\'ve added a description, duration, and other service details using Compose\'s Text elements and styled them for readability. The description is using the current theme. I have started the `CreateBookingScreen.kt` file.\n\n\n**Constructing Booking Flow**\n\nI\'m now building the CreateBookingScreen using Kotlin and Jetpack Compose. I\'ve designed the UI with a `Scaffold` for the app bar and content. I\'m using `LazyColumn` for a scrollable layout, and `Card` components for each booking step. I\'m integrating step-by-step components for address, date, and confirmation, and I\'ve incorporated icons to enhance clarity. I\'ve initialized state variables for the booking flow. I\'m making sure it\'s fully functional.\n\n\n\n**Refining Booking Navigation**\n\nI\'m now refining the navigation within the booking flow screen. I\'m implementing the back and next buttons within a bottom navigation bar. I\'ve integrated `IconButton` for back navigation with a back arrow icon, and I\'m updating `selectedStep` accordingly. The \"Next\" button updates the `selectedStep`. I have implemented conditional button visibility and logic.\n\n\n**Finalizing Booking Flow Implementation**\n\nI\'m now putting the finishing touches on the Booking Flow. I\'ve successfully incorporated the step-by-step components: Address, Date & Time, and Summary. I\'ve finished the conditional button logic for navigation between steps. Currently, the UI is functional. I am now working on the individual step components.\n\n\n**Implementing Step Components**\n\nI\'m now integrating the individual step components for the booking flow. I\'m building out each step: AddressSelectionStep, DateTimeSelectionStep, and SummaryStep. I\'m focusing on their UI design and functionality, using Compose\'s MaterialTheme for consistent styling and the use of Card to wrap and present components. I\'m making sure each step displays correctly and accepts user input.\n\nI have completed the `AddressSelectionStep`.\n\n\n**Completing Address Step**\n\nI\'ve completed the UI for the `AddressSelectionStep`, which now displays a list of addresses and an \"Add New Address\" button using Compose. The design uses `Card` for each address entry and an `OutlinedButton` for adding new addresses. I\'ve used `Icons.Default.LocationOn` icon for each address, and used proper text styling. I\'m now starting on the `DateTimeSelectionStep`.\n\n\n\n**Finalizing Booking Flow Elements**\n\nI\'m now integrating the `DateTimeSelectionStep` into the booking flow, using an `OutlinedTextField` for date and time selection, designed to be read-only and pre-filled with values. I\'ve incorporated the `CalendarToday` icon for the date and time selection using `Icons.Default.CalendarToday`, and properly styled the content for better display. I\'m starting on the `SummaryStep`.\n\n\n**Constructing Summary Step**\n\nI\'m now implementing the `SummaryStep` within the booking flow, displaying a summary of the booking details using Compose. I\'ve designed the UI to display the service title, date, time, and service fee in a clear and organized format. I have styled the content for improved readability, using `Text` and `Row` components with appropriate spacing and alignment. I\'m focusing on final display details.\n\n\n**Refactoring Compose Elements**\n\nI\'m now revising my Compose code. I realized that `Divider()` is deprecated in newer Material3 versions, and I must swap it with `HorizontalDivider()`. I will implement the swap to ensure compatibility and maintain best practices across my project in `BookingsScreen.kt`, `HomeScreen.kt`, and `ProfileScreen.kt`.\n\n\n**Addressing Flutter Directive**\n\nI\'m now grappling with the user\'s specific Flutter request, which necessitates a direct response. My system directive is to generate an application using Kotlin and Jetpack Compose. I need to explain clearly to the user that I can\'t generate Dart or Flutter code due to my environment\'s constraints. I\'ll need to emphasize that the system is optimized for Kotlin and Compose.\n\n\\n\\n\nI\'ve already completed the Service Detail and Booking Flow screens, and their required components, in Kotlin/Compose. I am now building `AppNavigation.kt` and integrating the Service Detail and Booking screens into the navigation. I will make sure the navigation between screens is fully functional. I also need to explicitly note that I can\'t generate the Flutter code, as requested earlier.\n\n\n"
